node.text:
Tried squatting 5 plates before this and absolutely sh*t the bed. I was not happy with the set and wasn’t walking away from the squat rack not satisfied. So after calling myself a little B word a few times I decided to do a fun little drop set seen here.
The goal was 20 reps... ended up getting 15 reps at 405lbs and just over 10 at 315lbs. Then I was able to limp away from the squat rack satisfied👌🏼
I’ll post the 5 plates set on @cbumfitness

node.text:
Did a set of 5 plates before this hoping it would feel light weight baby, but it was definitely heavy weight daddy so decided to torture myself with some high volume squats immediately after💀

🚨ALSO got something really exciting coming up, me and @melissabum are going to be having a transformation contest. With most peoples gyms opening back up it’s the perfect time to start some good habits and get back in shape or into your best shape.
You’ll be getting nutrition and training plans as well as check ins from either myself or Melissa to guide you through the process. We’re going to make it a fun sibling rivalry of team MelBum vs team Cbum with prizes for the best transformation.
With myself starting prep in a few weeks as well it’ll be like you guys are prepping with me.
I’ll have a lot more info to come at the beginning of next week so if your interested keep an eye out for the announcement👀

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Chris Bumstead on August 21, 2021 tagging @mrolympiallc, @ifbb_pro_league, and @dansolomon_official. May be an image of 2 people, biceps, beard and indoor.

node.text:
When I first switched over to Classic Physique I was shitty poser and a classic broke college student.
I couldn’t afford big fancy mirrors to practice, but luckily I found someone throwing away some old mirrored closet doors. I snagged them and set them up in my bedroom.
I pushed all my furniture in the corner, put my headphones on and taught myself how to pose by practicing every day.
Fast forward a few Olympias later and I felt it was only right to order some closet doors and continue to perfect what I was just learning back in 2016.
I honestly never imagined I would end up where I am, I was just taking it one step at a day and enjoying every second of it.
From that kid who should’ve been studying for exams posing in his college room, to stepping on the @mrolympiallc stage for the fifth time.
I am so grateful for every moment and opportunity that has lead me to where I am today, it’s a damn beautiful life.

A whole bunch of rows🤷🏻‍♀️
All my workouts are uploaded daily (slightly delayed) onto my @cbumfitness training app.
There are currently 6 splits to choose from, but I am personally following the “Olympia Prep” split (duhh).
Check it out at cbumfitness.com 🙏🏼

node.text:
Learn how to chase big dreams while understanding the end goal won’t make you happier.
Life’s and adventure meant to be enjoyed, not a means to an end.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Chris Bumstead on August 16, 2021 tagging @mrolympiallc, and @nicolas_tranchant. May be an image of 1 person and biceps.

node.text:
I don’t care how good you are, how good you think your are, or even how good you think I am.
Absolutely nothing is promised and winning never lasts as long as you think.
Every win you have is over the second you go home and you have to earn the next one.
I learned that real quick after winning my first Olympia, once the lights had faded I was left feeling much more empty than I imagined.
Only answer was to get back to work and do it again and again...
@mrolympiallc

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Chris Bumstead on August 09, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, biceps, beard and indoor.

node.text:
A few years back I had some health issues that have continued to affect me physically and mentally on and off through the years. I try not to talk about it as I don’t want to put my energy on it, but this past weekend was an exciting moment for me.
A huge thing I notice in my body is inflammation and water retention, especially after any form or “cheat meal” or lots of sodium. For this reason I have been much more health conscious and strict with my diet year round and really haven’t had any cheat meals during my preps, but I still have moments of fear and anxiety that it will come back.
This last weekend after Iain’s big win we went out and I indulged in a cheat meal because my body was in a good place.
For the first time since 2017 I woke up the next morning with no water retention actually looking better than the day before and the even bigger win for me was that I wasn’t anxious about my health.
It doesn’t mean I’ll never experience it again and I’ll most certainly still get some anxiety around it, but I am extremely grateful to be where I am at right now and learning to just enjoy the present and enjoy what is rather than fear what isn’t.
Shoulders and more shoulders @gymshark
